    "5.1.4), and the intractability of computing morally attractive Nash Equilibria (Sect. 5.1.5).",
    "(5) Any computational system that employ formal logic, e.g., for deontological rulefollowing, moral reasoning, or communication are subject to expressibility (sect. 5.2.1), intractability (Sect.",
    "5.2.2), and decidability (Sect. 5.2.3) issues that permeate the syntactics and semantics of logic.",
    "(6) Finally, it should be acknowledged that deontology is a family that encompasses a range of ethical theories that may in turn emphasize a range of different cognitive abilities and computational resources.",
    "It can be a moral rationalist project of finding universally justifiable and applicable rules on the basis of a shared autonomy and rationality."
